            <div class="about-text">
                <p class="bio-intro">
                    Hi, I'm Eliyahu, Eli for short. Most people find it difficult to
                    pronounce or remember after the first time, so Eli works just fine.
                </p>

                <p>
                    I grew up in Ghana and took an unconventional path into engineering. I moved 
                    to China to study <span class="accent">Electronics and Information Engineering</span>, which is really 
                    just a fancy way of saying telecommunications Engineering with some extras 
                    at <span class="accent">Nanjing University of Information Science and Technology</span>. 
                    That degree set the foundation, but the years that followed shaped how I actually think 
                    about technology. From 2021 to 2024, I worked across software development, 
                    data engineering, and eventually led a development team, building things, 
                    breaking things, and learning what it means to ship real products.
                </p>

                <p>
                    In 2024, I started my Master's in <span class="accent">Telecommunications Engineering</span>
                    at the <span class="accent">University of Maryland, College Park, USA</span> 
                    where I've gone deep into networking, routing protocols, network automation 
                    and infrastructure design. Outside the classroom, I run a homelab on 
                    <span class="accent">Proxmox</span> where I get to actually do the things 
                    I study: spinning up <span class="accent">Juniper vSRX routers,</span> 
                    automating deployments with <span class="accent">Ansible and Terraform,</span> 
                    and experimenting with configurations that would be expensive to touch 
                    in a production environment. The homelab is where theory becomes instinct.
                </p>

                <p>I'm also building <span class="accent">xUtility</span>, a personal web app that 
                    started as a way to practice full-stack development and evolved into 
                    something I actually use daily. It grows whenever I run into a problem 
                    worth solving.
                </p>

                <p>The bigger picture: <span class="accent">Africa's technology sector</span> 
                    is at an inflection point, and I want to be part of what comes next, 
                    particularly in telecommunications and network infrastructure. There's a 
                    lot of ground to cover, and I'm in no rush to stop learning.
                </p>

